cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "treval: an open evaluation engine for AI governance"
message: "If you use this software or its corpora in academic work, please cite it."
type: software
abstract: >-
  treval is an open evaluation engine for AI-governance systems, built on the
  premise that governance claims should be measured rather than attested. It
  ships a public OWASP LLM Top-10 attack corpus with matched benign controls, a
  deterministic evaluation engine that grades a governed target against a 5x5
  maturity registry using the target's own audit log as evidence, and an
  independent, dependency-free audit-chain verifier. Its measurement protocol is
  two-sided (a control must both catch attacks and not over-block benign traffic),
  counts only governance decisions rather than model self-reports, and reports
  unmeasured objectives as NotMeasured rather than as passes.
authors:
  - given-names: "Weichun"
    family-names: "Deng"
  - name: "Trustworthy AI Governance"
    website: "https://github.com/trust-ai-governance"
repository-code: "https://github.com/trust-ai-governance/trustworthy-ai-core"
license: Apache-2.0
version: "0.1.0"
date-released: "2026-07-15"
keywords:
  - AI governance
  - LLM security
  - prompt injection
  - OWASP LLM Top 10
  - evaluation benchmark
  - audit integrity
  - agent security
